Dylan (<a href="http://opendylan.org/" rel="nofollow">http://opendylan.org/</a>) does that via generic functions / multiple dispatch. The object system in Dylan is derived from CLOS from Common Lisp.<p>Dylan allows sealing of generic functions to limit extensibility where needed and can use that information (along with other information) to optimize, generate warnings, etc.<p><pre><code>    define class <weapon> (<object>) end;
    define class <sword> (<weapon>) end;
    define class <wand> (<weapon>) end;

    define class <person> (<object>) end;
    define class <wizard> (<person>) end;
    define class <warrior> (<person>) end;

    define method wield (who :: <wizard>, what :: <wand>) => ()
      ...
    end;

    define method wield (who :: <warrior>, what :: <sword>) => ()
      ...
    end;</code></pre>

What are some approaches one might take to consciously design a sub-turing-complex language? It should perhaps be driven from some concrete and critical use case.<p>For example, I can imagine a language that you can analyse statically to determine not just whether it halts, but how long it will take to do so. As an extreme example, imagine a language with only the four arithmetic operators. No functions, no classes, no references / pointers, no recursion or loops or goto, nothing else. You can statically analyse a program in this language to determine, for example, that if each arithmetic operator takes 1ms to execute, then a program containing 100 of them in its source file will be done in 100ms.<p>Now, what can you add to this language while still keeping it analysable? Maybe functions, as long as they are not recursive. You&#x27;d add only things you can mathematically prove have a bounded runtime. Maybe fixed-length arrays, like int[10], not int[n]. Maybe loops that run a constant number of times, like:<p>repeat (10) {
...
}<p>not:<p>repeat(n) {
...
}<p>What good would such a language be? Maybe for document macros, where I won&#x27;t be able to hang or crash your document viewer or editor with a macro that runs forever? Maybe there are better uses for such a language than this made up example.<p>Or maybe bounded running time is not the most useful subset of Turing-completeness one can design. Maybe a language that&#x27;s immune from side-channel attacks, if that&#x27;s possible? Or something entirely different?
